{{ill|Takeinadane|ja|建稲種命}} was a Japanese warrior. He is worshjipped as a [[kami]] of [[Atsuta Shrine]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Introduction {{!}} ATSUTA JINGU |url=https://www.atsutajingu.or.jp/en/intro/ |access-date=2023-10-23 |website=www.atsutajingu.or.jp}}</ref>

''Nihonshoki'' explains that this move occurred in the 51st year of Keiko's reign, but shrine tradition also dates this event in the 1st year of Emperor Chūai's reign.<ref name="Ponsonby-Fane-2016">{{Cite book |last=Ponsonby-Fane |first=R. A. B. |title=Studies In Shinto & Shrines |date=2016-05-11 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-138-98322-9 |edition=1st |language=English |chapter=Atsuta Jingu}}</ref>{{rp|435}} The Owari clan established the [[Atsuta Shrine]] in 192, and held the position of the shrine's high priest since ancient times, passing it down from generation to generation.<ref name="Naito-1975">{{Cite book |last=Naito |first=Toho |title=Choshu Zasshi (張州雑志) |publisher=Aichi-ken Kyōdo Shiryō Kankō-kai |year=1975 |doi=10.11501/9537297}}</ref> [[Yamato Takeru]] and {{ill|Miyazu-hime|ja|宮簀媛}} and her brother {{ill|Takeinadane|ja|建稲種命}} are worshipped at the shrine.<ref name="Ponsonby-Fane-2016" />{{rp|429}}

The venerated Shinto deities of [[Tagata Shrine]] are Mitoshi (御歳神, Mitoshi-no-kami) and female deity Tamahime (玉姫命, Tamahime-no-mikoto). Mitoshi is the son of the Shinto male deity [[Toshigami]] (年神) or known by local as Ōtoshi (大歳神, Ōtoshi-no-kami) and grandson of the Shinto deity [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo]]. Tamahime is a princess and the daughter of Ō'arata (大荒田命, Ō'arata-no-Mikoto), the matriarch of [[Owari clan|''Owari'' clan]] (尾張氏) of her husband {{ill|Takeinadane|ja|建稲種命}} (健稲種命, Take'inadane-no-mikoto) who were blessed with two sons and four daughters. After her husband's death, she returned to his hometown Arata (situated close to Komaki), encouraged to cultivate with the help of her father Ō'arata, honor and achieved his achievements.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Small village gets real big at ancient celebration |url=https://www.mcasiwakuni.marines.mil/Iwakuni-News/News-Stories/News-Article-Display/Article/506486/small-village-gets-real-big-at-ancient-celebration/https%3A%2F%2Fwww.mcasiwakuni.marines.mil%2FIwakuni-News%2FNews-Stories%2FNews-Article-Display%2FArticle%2F506486%2Fsmall-village-gets-real-big-at-ancient-celebration%2F |access-date=2023-11-18 |website=Marine Corps Air Station Iwakuni, Japan |language=en-US}}</ref>

